ABUJA – Following the physical assault on the former Deputy President of the Senate, Ike Ekweremadu, in Nuremberg, Germany, by Indigenous People of Biafra (IPOB), the Senate Chief Whip, Orji Uzor Kalu, on Monday, denied suspending his medical trip to Germany. Kalu, who said that there was never a time he suspended his planned medical trip, described reports of the suspension as totally untrue and figment of the writer’s imagination. Powered by RubiQube Ad Network The Senate Chief Whip, in a statement by his media office, said that since the National Assembly went on recess, he has been in his country home, Igbere, interacting with members of his constituency. He said: “I have been in my country home interacting with the people (of my constituency) and settling disputes. The news that I suspended by planned medical check-up in Germany was not true. “I was invited by Igbo group in Spain to attend their function; I could not go because of the interaction with my constituents.” Describing the action of the IPOB members against Senator Ekweremadu as uncivilised, unacceptable and barbaric, Kalu said that the assault was a slap on Igbo leaders regardless of party affiliation. The former governor of Abia State described Ekweremadu as a prominent Nigerian who deserves to be respected. Kalu, therefore, urged Igbos to respect their leaders at all levels and embrace peace, saying only then will the South-East region be prosperous was by embracing.